 HARDNESS RATING: 8/10

    Here's the breakdown:

    Aspect: Custom node class (TypeScript)
    Difficulty: 3/10
    Reasoning: n8n's node API is well-documented. A node that receives input and returns transformed data is very straightforward
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Generating HTML from a node
    Difficulty: 4/10
    Reasoning: Template strings, compile JSX, or integrate with an HTML templating library
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: n8n Data Table for persistent storage
    Difficulty: 3/10
    Reasoning: n8n already has a Data Table node. Using it from a custom node is just API calls
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Auth / sessions / JWT
    Difficulty: 5/10
    Reasoning: Running web server auth inside n8n's workflow engine isn't what it's built for. Have to interact with the HTTP lifecycle, cookies,
      request/response objects at n8n's periphery
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Page rendering with sub-node assembly
    Difficulty: 7/10
    Reasoning: n8n's Cluster Node system (root + sub-nodes) is there, but dynamically composing UI components at runtime from node definitions is not its design
      purpose. The Page node would need to inspect its own sub-nodes, execute them, and collect their output — all at runtime
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Multi-page routing (App Router)
    Difficulty: 7/10
    Reasoning: n8n executes workflows in isolation. Coordinating across workflows (route → auth → page → components) means building a custom runner on top of the
      n8n engine
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Deploy node / packaging
    Difficulty: 6/10
    Reasoning: Dockerizing an n8n instance with a baked config is easy. Dockerizing it so it starts up automatically and serves at a single endpoint is
      moderately challenging
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Frontend SPA rendering
    Difficulty: 8/10
    Reasoning: n8n produces JSON from nodes. Turning that into an interactive single-page app (with routing, state updates, partial page refreshes) without
      shipping a React/Next.js codebase is the big one. This is where the project has to decide: interpret nodes as a frontend or compile from node definitions
      into a separate frontend framework
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Overall integration
    Difficulty: 8.5/10
    Reasoning: Making all these pieces work together WITHOUT node.js framework code, all within n8n's model/run/complete execution cycle
    ────────────────────────────────────────
    Aspect: Making it feel production-grade**
    Difficulty: 9/10
    Reasoning: Fast load times, error states, loading indicators, responsive design, accessibility, browser history, mobile support. polish is a beast on a
      platform that wasn't meant to do this

    P80 estimate: 2-3 months solo

    - 2 weeks: functional custom node that renders HTML
    - 1 month: basic Page node with sub-node assembly
    - 2 months: Auth + Data Table CRUD
    - 3 months: App Router with multi-page navigation + a minimal end-to-end Todo app
    - Remaining: Deploy node, SSG/SSR split, polish, edge cases

    Counterfactual: building the same thing in Python with FastAPI directly would be simpler and actually faster to develop, BUT you lose the visual
    drag-drop UI and the 400+ n8n integrations. The hardness lives in the constraint: all inside n8n.
